ce:section.ce:para:
The existence of the formation of CD@RCC3 was first confirmed by Fourier transform infrared spectroscopy (FT-IR, Fig. 2
                        a). For the bare CDs, strong CO and OH stretching vibrations at 1720 cm−1 and 3433 cm−1 are observed (Fig. 2a-1), indicating plentiful carboxyl groups on CDs surface. Once the CDs reacted with SOCl2, the strong CO stretching vibrations at 1720 cm−1 shifted to a higher frequency at 1768 cm−1 (Fig. 2a–2). The carboxyl groups on CDs surface can be reacted with SOCl2 to produce acylchloride group, rendering the strong CO stretching vibrations at 1720 cm−1 shifted to a higher frequency 1768 cm−1. The FT-IR spectra of RCC3 has an absorption band at 3429 cm−1 (Fig. 2a-3
                        ) assigned to the stretching vibration of NH, and the two peaks at 2936 cm−1 and 2862 cm−1 are ascribed to the stretching vibration of CH2
                        . For CD@RCC3, the strong NH stretching vibration at 3428 cm−1 and CH2
                         stretching vibrations at 2925 cm−1 and 2852 cm−1 are observed (Figs. 2a–4
                        ), which suggests that bare CDs have been successfully attached to RCC3 via amide bond. Thermogravimetric analyses were performed for comparison of CDs, RCC3, CD@RCC3. As shown in Fig. 2b, a weight loss of around 56% of CDs (Fig. 2b-1) occurring at 325 °C is observed, which is likely attributed to the removal of carboxylic acid groups on the surface of the CDs. Meanwhile, a weight loss of 24% corresponds to the loss of amide group of CD@RCC3 occurred at 325 °C (Fig. 2b–2), while RCC3 almost remains stable under this temperature (Fig. 2b-3). These results support that CDs have been incorporated successfully with RCC3 to form CD@RCC3 composites.
